0,/Hotel_Review-g186338-d193046-Reviews-or0-The_Dilly-London_England.html#REVIEWS,"The Dilly Hotel Reviews, London",Just OK,"The good - the communal areas of this hotel are lovely. The reception is very impressive with a large floral display which on closer inspection turned out to also be a florists shop. The Terrace bar where breakfast is served is also impressive, and the restaurant to the left of reception was closed, but also looked impressive. However first appearances can be a little deceptive, and this was a bit of an ‚Äòall fur coat and no knickers‚Äô scenario.  I booked a 5 night stay just as the UK was coming out of lockdown so thought I had a good deal for a standard room, at what is advertised as a five star hotel. The hotel is good but not what I would term five star. My room was OK, a nice comfortable double bed, small armchair, desk and large shower room. I understand that there is covid so there may be other things that had been removed, but a comforter and pillows would have made the room more inviting.   There was a lamp stand in the corner of the room but the wire was still coiled up and not plugged in, this was because there was simply no plugs in the corner where it had been abandoned.  In the wardrobe I found the tea tray, kettle, tea bags, four small portions of milk. No biscuits. Even the Travelodges manage to leave a packet of shortbread in their rooms! There was a safe and iron also in the wardrobe and a mini bar which apparently I could have asked the hotel to add stock to it, but it was empty during my stay.   So far so good, except the first night there I was freezing! The heating did not work at all during my stay. And the thin duvet did not provide much warmth so I got up and put the dressing gown over me. The best feature of the room was the dressing gown ‚Äì as the hotel has been rebranded from Le Meridien to The Dilly the dressing gown was very new. I also had issues in the bedroom with getting some of the lamps to work. I found out on my third morning that one of the switches by the door was a ‚Äòmaster switch‚Äô and that had to be on for some of the lamps to work. Unfortunately nothing in the room pointed out this important piece of information as the usual guide to hotel services has been removed, I guess because of covid and replaced with QR codes. However none of the information the QR codes linked to gave out this quite important bit of information.   On the second night someone had put a radiator in my room so I was able to control the temperature much better.    The bathroom was also disappointing for a hotel that bills itself as five star and apparently has been recently remodelled. The towels left out for my first night were small and threadbare. On day two, although I had not mentioned anything to reception someone left a pile of brand new towels in my room while I was at breakfast, larger bath sheets. But inexplicably removed all the face cloths including the ones I had not used. I needed the towels as the heated towel rail was not heated at all, except briefly on my second day when someone apparently fixed it after I mentioned it at reception. But it has stopped working again by the following day. So there was no way of getting the towels dry as the bathroom extractor fan did not appear to be working either.   The sink and vanity counter in the bathroom was large and appeared newish. The vanity mirror was nowhere near a light fitting which suggests it was badly thought out.  The shower was very poor. The shower fitting itself did not really fit in the holder as the wrong type of pipe had been used, a rigid pipe which meant the shower head was fixed in a strange position where water came out horizontally. And the strength of the water left much to be desired ‚Äì no overhead rain shower, just a small shower which the water struggled out of, making rinsing my hair a much lengthier process than it should have been. There were nice toiletries from Floris but that was the most positive thing about the bathroom. I had rinsed one of the mugs out after my tea and left it on the sink when I went out. It was still there when I came back although the room had been serviced!  I had booked a rate which included breakfast. And again I guess because of Covid this was a spartan affair ‚Äì no offers of toast, no cereal, no fresh fruit, no yoghurt unless you chose the granola/porridge/yoghurt option from the menu in which case it did not appear as if you would be able to choose anything else. My first morning I chose poached eggs ‚Äì these were OK but came with two slices of mediocre, dried out, brown toast, no butter or sauces offered. I tried the scrambled eggs on brioche the following day, which were an improvement but apart from the small piece of brioche the eggs were artistically arranged on, there was no offer of additional toast.  The third morning I chose pastries which were small, cold and had been overcooked and I had to ask for some jam and butter for the croissants, which seemed to come as a surprise request to the waitress. The staff were all very pleasant and hard working but the prices on the menu were ridiculous and I cannot imagine anyone paying the amount mentioned on the menu would be happy with what was served for breakfast. I‚Äôve stayed at seaside B&Bs which did a whole heap better than this at providing guests with breakfast, including offering decent bread to be toasted rather than the cheapest supermarket sliced loaf which is what was on offer at the Dilly. I finally got breakfast right on my final morning by requesting poached eggs on sourdough - the sourdough was mentioned as an accompaniment to another breakfast offering, omlette.  Still only one small piece of sourdough with two poached eggs though.  There are a very large number of hotels in London, and all have lost money and business during the two lockdowns there have been in England in the last 14 months. They can no longer rely on business travellers now so many people have realised that it is possible to meet virtually without having to travel and stay away from home. Hotels will need to try to appeal more to leisure travellers and to attract repeat travellers if they are to stay on business‚Ä¶",Date of stay: May 2021,3.0
